\section*{Densities}
\begin{problem}
Answer the following questions:
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*)]
  \item Can a probability density function (pdf) ever take values greater than 1?
  \item Let $X$ be a univariate normally distributed random variable with mean 0
        and variance $1/100$. What is the pdf of $X$?
  \item What is the value of this pdf at 0?
  \item What is the probability that $X = 0$?
  \item Explain the discrepancy.
\end{enumerate}
\end{problem}

\noindent\textbf{Solution}

\noindent\textbf{(a)} Yes, as long as it still integrates to 1. For example, take the uniform distribution on the interval $[0,a]$ for $a < 1$. Then in order for the total probability to equal 1, we must have that the pdf $f(x) = \frac{1}{a} >1$ over the interval $[0,a]$ (and $f(x) = 0$ otherwise).

\medskip

\noindent\textbf{(b)} Let $f(x)$ be the pdf of $X$. Then 
\begin{align*}
 X \sim \mathcal{N}(0,\frac{1}{100}) \implies f(x) &= \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\cdot\frac{1}{100}}} \exp\left(-\frac{(x-0)^2}{2\cdot\frac{1}{100}}\right)\\
 &= \sqrt{\frac{50}{\pi}} \exp(-50x^2)
\end{align*}

\noindent\textbf{(c)} $$f(0) = \sqrt{\frac{50}{x}}$$

\noindent \textbf{(d)} $$P(X=0) = 0$$

\noindent\textbf{(e)} In short, a probability \textit{density} is not the same as a probability. Since a PDF is defined over a continuous (in particular, uncountably infinite) interval, the probability that it will take on any particular value is 0 (consider that if not, then we would sum an uncountably infinite number of positive values, which would certainly not have sum equal to 1, as is required of a probability distribution). Only intervals of positive length have nonzero probability. This is why in part (a), we have that a pdf can take values greater than 1, despite probabilities themselves being unable to have values greater than 1.




